gs":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":0,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":13,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":22,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Brokesby was born in 1315, in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England. He married Mrs. Robert de Brokesby about 1334, in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1340, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1315–1340":"1315–1340","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1336–1400":"1336–1400","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","about 1315":"umbes 1315","about 1334":"umbes 1334","1340":"1340","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England","Melton Morbray, Leicester, England, United Kingdom":"Melton, Transvaal, Lõuna-Aafrika"},"fi":{"1315–1340":"1315–1340","1315–Female":"1315–Kuollut","1336–1400":"1336–1400","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","about 1315":"noin 1315","about 1334":"noin 1334","1340":"1340","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England","Melton Morbray, Leicester, England, United Kingdom":"Melton, Transvaal, Etelä-Afrikka"},"fr":{"1315–1340":"1315–1340","1315–Female":"1315–Décédée","1336–1400":"1336–1400","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","about 1315":"environ 1315","about 1334":"environ 1334","1340":"1340","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, Engl